<HEADLINE>
OT Radio (long)
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<POST>
<POSTER> Daniel Nestlerode &lt;dnest...@mindspring.com&gt; </POSTER>
<POSTDATE> 2007-08-11T02:11:00 </POSTDATE>
[OK.  Call me Captain OT.  Whatever.  I'm having fun and you guys are a good
audience. ;-)]

Six years ago my wife's grandmother, Gladys, decided to leave the house that
she had bought with her late husband Carl in nineteen-fifty-something for
about $6000.00 (no, I did not miss a zero) in favor of a studio in a
retirement community nearby.  Carl had been gone for 25 years and Gladys had
lived alone all that time.

One of the joys of Gladys's life was going to Longs Drugs and buying
whatever item happened to be on sale in quantities too large for a single
elderly woman.  So when she sold her home to my brother-in-law and his wife,
we had a lot of clearing out to do.  The writers of &quot;Friends&quot; (TV Show from
the 90s) hit the nail on the head when Ross found his Noni's secret stash of
Sweet-n-Low and was deluged with little pink packets.  Gladys fit the
profile exactly, except she's still alive. ;-)

We found boxes of 10 year old saltines, Oreos, and cans of vegetables
resting comfortably in an unused bedroom closet.  We collected more packages
of paper towels and toilet paper than you could shake a stick at.  Shoes she
had never worn (and never will wear) seemed to come from some bottomless pit
under the bed in that back bedroom.

But we also found some interesting stuff: a little ukulele brought back from
Hawaii, some of Carl's old cigarette lighters, and a Zenith chairside radio
in full Art Deco glory.  For you radio geeks it's a Zenith 9S244 with a 75
watt amplifier, built in 1939. The wood cabinet is in excellent shape,
though it is missing it's plate glass control panel cover.

The radio was dead, but beautiful and I knew that I would someday have it
repaired.  So I claimed it and we stored it.  The radio moved from town to
town with us, un-repaired, until we landed here in Modesto.  Then it landed
in my garage for 3 and a half more years.  It survived 115 degree (F) heat
waves and actual freezing temperatures.  It survived the demolition of the
old shake and shingle roofs and the installation of the new composite
shingle roof.  It survived numerous adoptions by spiders, a few of them were
black widows.

Finally, in April I took into a funky old shop downtown called Radio
Electronics (of all things).  The guy who runs it, Leroy, is in his 70s and
has only a rudimentary grasp of electronics not related directly to video or
sound production.  The credit card reader is a mystery to him; the
printer/fax/copier is an infernal machine.

The place is a radio geek's heaven.  It's a fire hazard of narrow passage
ways ancient wooden steps, and low ceilinged alcoves festooned with circuit
boards, pegboards, CRT tubes, amp tubes, wires, stereo components in every
stage of disrepair, and wondrous little doo-hickies that light up and find
broadcast signals or read 78s, 45s, 33s, CDs, tapes, and DVDs.

Late last week, we got a call.  The radio was ready and we could come pick
it up.  We were away, they left a message.  They a second message on Monday
morning.  Monday evening, just minutes after coming in off the road and
hearing the messages, the phone rang again.  It was Leroy.  I could tell he
was excited.  He had managed a *complete* repair despite some severe
obstacles, like a warped chassis, deteriorated belts, hardened lubricating
grease, and bent control shafts.

The repair required skill and ingenuity, and the radio was a worthy
recipient of his efforts.  He recreated rivets, he bored out parts of the
chassis to accommodate a slightly longer replacement belt, he ran a tension
wire from one corner of the chassis to another to counter the warping and
make all of the shafts slide inside one another perfectly.  He used small
bits of rubber tire inner tube to replace the old, dried, and hardened
rubber mounting rings.  Genius.

I went down to pick it up today.  Leroy spent an hour explaining the
repairs, the repair process, and showing me how the radio worked.  He was
clearly proud, and I was happy to share the success with him.

When I brought it home and plugged it in, it was magical. The dial and
controls are in the shape of a rounded isosceles triangle with a circular
frequency dial.  On the left corner is the 3 position &quot;On&quot; switch (Off, On
Local, and On Distance).  On the right is the volume control.  On the top is
the 5 position tone control switch; it's almost a notch filter.  Bottom
center is a 3 part concentric switch with which the user chooses the band
(AM, Shortwave, and REALLY Shortwave), turns the dial to fine tune the
radio, and runs a motor driven quick tuner to get around the dial fast.

When you switch bands, the dial face splits in two and the halves slide into
a recesses on either side of the triangle.  When you tune, you can visually
gauge the power of the signal by watching how close to creating a full
circle a little green florescent light appears.

The tone is amazing, it beats the hell out of any AM radio made in the last
30 years.  The 75 watt amp has a lot of power and is pretty transparent.
The Giants never sounded so good losing to &lt;shudder&gt; the Pirates after
dropping two of the last three to &lt;double shudder&gt; the Nats.

The whole thing is a combination of innovative design, good engineering,
genius repair, beautiful sound, hip retro controls, and my good sense to
spent about $300.00 on an old radio.

Now I'm looking into buying or making an antenna suitable to catch some of
the best frequencies on the shortwave band.

I'm telling you all of this because I have discovered the coolest radio
station in existence.  There's a US Dept of standards or something (KAIJ) in
Denver broadcasting the most useful stuff a musician could ever want: an
A=440 tone, a pulse every second, and the time (Greenwich Meantime) every
minute.  Get a shortwave radio and you'll never need a tuner.
;-)

Daniel
