Daniel, that was not at all long.  It was great!  Thanks for sharing.
You did good getting the old beauty to working again.  I have restored
a few of these old radios but not the multibands ones.  They can be a
handful but I have learned that when they drove me crazy, I was in a
hurry and had a lot of other things in want of doing.

Later, I would spend a few hours rewiring it and then quit for a beer,
sit outside a while, and later go back to it.  Then it became fun.

My Heathkit audio amp still works fine.  I built it in 1952...it has
been rebuilt a few times though.

My problem with these old radios is that when I turn them on and the
golden glow of the celluloid dial lights up and I tune in a
station...I don't get &quot;Just Plain Bill&quot; or &quot;Lights Out&quot;...I
get...well...you know what I get.

I have a couple of solutions for this.  I have one of the old 1930
radio cabinets on a shelf in the bar with a couple of good speakers in
it.  I turn it on and the magic eye lights up as does the dial...but
nothing else happens because that is the only things that have power
in it.

Then I turn on my out-of-sight  CD player and it plays through the
speakers in the old cabinet.  And I have a good source of old radio
programs.  I just gave my wife a CD with 115 &quot;Gun Smoke&quot; radio
programs.  I have tons of &quot;Light Crush Dough Boys,&quot; &quot;Harry Richman
Radio Show,&quot; etc.

It does sound funny though when Harry's good voice says, &quot;Fred, I went
by the store the other day to take a look at a real beauty.  Have you
seen the new 1938 Dodge!&quot;

And I have to share this...Matt Dillon says, &quot;I've come for the girl.
Jane, are you OK?  Mister, you can't take someone's daughter to settle
a debt.  Now, don't do anything foolish and try to draw on me....&quot;
Then &quot;BANG!  BANG!  BANG!&quot;  There is a pause and you hear a body
hitting the floor.  Another long pause, and you hear Marshall Dillon:
&quot;Just step over him, Jane.&quot;

Ahhh...radio!

Ken
