I remember him more from radio than from TV.  He is made fun of a lot
but this comes from his last egomaniacal days.  He helped a lot of
people be discovered and the list of these names is unbelievable.

Godfrey had live radio and TV programs going on the same day and near
every day of the week.  CBS owner, Palley, hated him; the CBS
president loved him...because his shows were cheap to produce and they
brought in a lot of money.  His big production shows cost what cheap
game shows cost, yet for three years this one guy brought in 12% of
CBS's annual income.  For something like eight years, it was over 8%.

The people Godfrey discovered were supposed to be a part of his &quot;on
air&quot; family but Godfrey was always on the air.  (Lawrence Welk had a
little bit of this in him, as well.)

Godfrey required &quot;his&quot; people get dental make overs, go to dancing
classes, etc., but La Rosa's problems started when he started &quot;seeing&quot;
one of the McGuire sisters, who were other &quot;little Godfreys.&quot;  Then La
Rosa had a big hit record produced independently of Godfrey, and the
last straw was when La Rosa hired an agent/manager.

This was a big &quot;no-no.&quot;  Godfrey was everyone's
agent/manager/counselor/Big Daddy.  Then La Rosa didn't show up for
dance classes.  &lt;g&gt;  Godfrey was already mad at his show-band because
the leader/owner of the band had used the band to back La Rosa on some
recordings and no one had asked Godfrey if that was OK.

Godfrey told the CBS president he (Godfrey) was firing La Rosa on the
air because he had hired him on the air.  The president (it is said)
agreed.  Later, Godfrey said it was the president's idea.  I doubt
this, but the president would agree to do about anything the
vindictive 12%er wanted.

Julius was fired because &quot;he had lost his humility&quot; Godfrey said.  The
press knew Godfrey and they started hitting on him pretty hard because
Godfrey was as far from humble as a fellow could get.  He wasn't like
his public persona.  (Two weeks later, he fired the entire band...but
not on the air.  They came in for a rehearsal and the replacement band
was already set up.)

Godfrey was a pilot and his number and type of aircraft (for the day),
would rival Travolta's, but once Godfrey was on downwind leg for his
home field of Teterbourgh, NJ, an airliner had a problem and Godfrey
was told to make another circuit of the traffic pattern.

This made him mad and Godfrey stayed in the traffic pattern until the
base leg-to-final turn, elongated it, and flew his DC-3 right in front
of the towers windows.

The FAA gave him hell for this.  He was fined and they banned him from
Teterbough and made him move his operation to another field.  Then
Godfrey got on the FAA's case and said on a major TV interview that
America needed the SST like they needed more chunks of rocks from the
moon.  The US SST program was doomed immediately.  Nixon was not
pleased.  &lt;g&gt;

One other note -- and it would make a good story now...Godfrey was a
smoker big time until he had hip replacement (one of the earlier ones
to do this) and he later had lung cancer.  He died from emphysema ...
caused by the radiation he had received for lung cancer treatment.

I had an aunt who nearly died directly from radiation treatment.  An
interesting read would be of the early uses of such treatments and the
damage done while the medical people were learning to use it.

I am babbling again, aren't I...jeez!

Ken
