I modify antiques all the time but not in any way they cannot be put
back like they were...and often in less time than it took to modify
them.  Never put holes in those things but they have vent holes that
wires could run through...the problem with coupling a modern device to
them though is one of impedance (there, I used that word).

The vacuum stuff is high impedance and the xister stuff low.  The
first amps we had were the same ones that Les Paul had.  Tune to an
off station and have the input lead from the wiper of the volume
control with the shield going to ground as close to the wiper as
possible.  This is often the other side of the volume control.

You are right, sports on the radio is the same as yesterday, and a lot
music is, as well.  I have a WWII bomber receiver in this room and it
is often on a BBC station (or WWV).  &lt;g&gt;

It seems funny but most of the a.m. I was listening to 1950s Les Paul
radio shows...and the Light Crush Dough Boys.  All this computer
technology to listen to mp3s of old time radio programs.

Maybe the Twilight Zone radio was picking up original xmissions that
have traveled in space and are looping back after being reflected from
something.

Ken
